Disney + subscriber nos have been revealed in April (?) to have surpassed 50 million. This includes international markets like India, and people accessing Disney + for free (while being subsidized by someone else - like their ISP).
Based on: https://www.cnet.com/news/disney-plus-surpasses-50-million-subscribers-in-five-months/

With the recent launch of Disney+ in Europe and the effects of CoronaVirus forcing people to stay at home Disney+ released preliminary numbers at the beginning of the month with a subscriber count of already surpassing 50 million. Considering that since the launch of Disney+ only 5 months ago it has already racked up 50 million paying subscribers its rate of growth says it should be upwards of 55 million. I don't expect a drop-off anytime soon either as market leader Netflix has over 170 million paying subscribers many of whom pay for multiple streaming services as well. I think it's also important to note that none of the market leading streaming platforms are present in China. Disney as a cooperation has had a strong history with China and although this may not produce direct number growth by may 12th its promising for investors and supporters of the platform.

Disney+ hit 50 million subscribers as of 4/8, and that number will not decline by 5/12 thanks to promotional offers and shelter-in-place requirements. The only question is whether that will increase another 5 million by 5/12. Considering they've almost doubled subscribers from the 28.6M they ended with in Q1, they likely have the momentum to finish the quarter above this mark.

Press reports are that subscribers hit 50m at some point during the period in question, but a little vague. The reason for a small alloc to the 'will not report' is that it is possible the company may not want to highlight these figures given the potentially unseemly aspect, i.e. company benefitting from COVID . I think that's a very low probability (5%) but it isn't zero.

Disney has already hit 50 mil+ subscribers and is quite likely to overshoot the 55 mil mark by a margin, by the time the results of its second quarters are announced. Disney reported 26.5 million subscribers in Q1 2020 which, according to the CEO, increased to 28.6 million (https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/04/disney-plus-subscriber-numbers-26point5-million.html). The service has since been released into some of the most populous European countries including the UK, Germany, Spain and Italy. It will be released in France soon. Since people are having to spend more time at home it follows that there will be an increase in the number of subscriptions.

Rough: 1) On Feb 3 it had 28.6m (from Q1 conf. call). This was +2.1m from end December. 2) From Antenna analytics chart (https://medium.com/antennaanalytics/the-impact-of-covid-19-disney-sign-ups-spike-d178456435eb) it had roughly same increment from Feb 3 to March 14th (+2.1m, cumulatively c.31m). 4) From March 14th onwards, Antenna estimate of virus = 2.6x uptick in daily signups vs. 2020 average. (Extrapolating adds c.2.2m in USA to month end, cumulatively c.33m) 5) Launch of 7 European countries on 24th. Assuming this is c.85% of Nov launch population & they are 75% as interested in Disney, that's +c.6.5m on day 1 (day 1 in Nov. was 10m). Cumulatively c.40m. 6) Assume incremental c.2.2m in Europe from launch to end Q2 (from Nov. launch daily run rate after first day). Cumulatively c.42m.

March 22, 2020: By the end of Diney's Q2 they will be available in 7 countries. Netflix has a subscription rate of ~20% in these countries. Disney+ currently has ~27M subscribers (7.4% in these countries). D+ is cheaper the NFLX and the at the break point of 35M (~10%) I believe that D+ will reach that but definitely won't go above 55M (~15.6%) subscribers. Verizon cross promotion offer may increase +/- 1M subscriptions but won't impact.

Minor updates in numbers due to changing situation - India and France launch delayed - Perhaps more interest than expected in the EU due to lockdowns. Conversely there is lower streaming quality due to throttling but I don't expect that to affect subscriber numbers much.

I have changed my prediction to a 63% possibility that Disney+ will have more than 55M paying customers by the end of 2Q20 due to a new announcement that was just released by Deadline that states that, "Up to 50% of U.S. internet users with children under 10 in their households have already subscribed to the Disney+ streaming service" [1]. According to Statista.com, there are approximately 18,414,550 families in the United States (as of 2019) that have at least one child under the age of 11 [2]. Further, the Deadline article states that "more than four in 10 (41%) of 18- to 24-year-olds say they already have access to the service" [1]. According to Marketingcharts.com, there are appx 30.5M individuals in this age group [3].

As of now the number is 28.6 million (1). It launched in US, Canada, Netherlands, Australia and New Zealand in Q1. Comparing with Netflix, which has roughly 90 million Netflix subscribers in those countries as of 2019 (2), Disney having roughly 1/3 of that number through Q1 Disney will Launch in the UK, Germany, Italy, Austria, Spain, France, Ireland and Switzerland in Q2. (3) The Netflix subscribers in those countries are roughly 36 million. (2). Streaming revenue in the US is roughly double that of Europe. (4). Therefore i will take a conservative 6th of the Q2 netflix subscriptions (36 million) = 6 million.

Subscriber growth beat expectations in Q1. Further growth in Q2 will include international expansion (harder to accomplish and more costly). Disney mgt is transitioning but subscriber growth seems to be expected since commentary is for subscriber income to compensate for potential park closings due to Coronavirus. Growth unlikely to beat Q1 but also less likely to fail badly - which will be suggested by a NR of Q2 subscriber growth.
Considering their current standing the might exceed 35ml

At their current growth rates, i expect 31-33 million 'paying' subscriber figures for Disney+ in the US, but the launching in Europe in late March may bring in 2-4 million new subscribers in the first week. That put the figure at 33-37 million which is just finely balanced.

Disney+ had 26.5 million subscribers at December 28th 2019. Bob Iger reported that they had 28.6 million on February 3rd 2020 - a 2.1 million growth for the month of January. Assuming a similiar growth for February and March (when their 2nd quarter ends), would suggest around 33 million US subscribers.

Disney have already reported on their first quarter results so no reason to assume they won't report on second quarter hence the low percentage for the final option. They have already reported 26.5 million on it's first quarter in the US and the CEO has provided an update that the number is up to 28.6million on Feb 3rd. Verizon have been offering free Disney access to new and existing customers (which disney will count as paying -20% of disney subscribers are from verizon but 17million will be eligible according to verizon ceo). Netflix reported 167million subscribers at the end of Q4 so a conservative estimate of 15% of users willing to pay for double services makes 25million additional. Europe launching at promotional offer of £49.99 makes it highly attractive to encourage early sign ups. Growth in the U.S. is likely to slow, but the expansion into Europe in March should put it over the 35.0 million mark. Overall, I would expect to see an increase in subscription services over the next quarter as people limit social activities dues to COVID-19 fears.
Existing markets (UCAN+Oceania): grew ~2.1mil in Jan 2020. Assuming same growth, +4mil by Mar 2020. - Assumption: nCov boost + slowing subscriber growth in existing markets should cancel out.

Netflix has around 40-50 million subscriptions in Europe. So lets say (zipfs law) 20% of them are willing to wither double purchase or leave a subscription service. So 8-9 million people up for grabs. Add that to the 29 million (Im adding lag to the 26.5) and we are looking at 37-38 million. So already we can see that an optimistic outlook places it above the 35 mark.

The first quarter was about 29 million... Netflix raised it subscription fee whereas Disney+ has a low introductory fee so more will switch from Netflix to Disney+ as families find more varied content on Disney+

A Feb 3 report showed Disney+ at 28.6 mil putting growth at 2.1 million in a month. Netflix was at 62 mil (167 wordwide) and Hulu at 30.4. The service is set to launch in UK, Ireland, France, Germany, Italy, Spain, Austria, and Switzerland on March 24 with further launches in Western Europe markets, including Belgium, the Nordics, and Portugal, following in summer 2020. This is not all of Europe. Video streaming revenue in Europe is roughly half of the US (https://www.statista.com/outlook/206/102/video-streaming--svod-/europe). If the rate remains the same, that would yield an additional 14 mil subscribers (assuming a two month ramp is sufficient). Need to consider the lack of Belgium, the nordics, and Portugal. However, "at home" services may receive a boost from the coronavirus. Putting it all together, I see a growth between 16-20 million additional users in Q1
Netflix has 150mln, Amazon 40mln, but Disney has much lower choice, marketing expenses etc, plus they had only 2mln growth per q

Factors. Intl. launch delay risk vs COVID tail wind/head wind. My Point estimate is 39m. 28.6m as of Feb 3. Vs 26.5m at Dec 31. So 2m net adds without extra launches. —> 30m at end of Q without new launches. Uk, france, Germany, Italy, Spain (pion approx 250m) are launching due March 24 - so about 7 days for those new countries. This puts it on the 33m to 42m type of range, but could have single demand. Plus India supposedly launches on March 29 (?!) so there is launch day in India to consider. I’m making a 39m point estimate without over thinking.
